Information on the issue is very easy to find, however, given that discord disallows discussion around exploits and the nature of discords like ours being commonly monitored for this type of stuff, we want to try to give people as much of a head start on updating and securing. Please be aware we will not describe how this exploit works, what it does, or any of the details - rest assured it is very serious and you absolutely should update immediately. We also ask that you do not share misleading, false, or accurate details of the exploit or its fixes

For **all versions of java this can be a massive issue***, but not a concern to those using versions of paper we've patched. 

All builds on the website are patched and available to download: https://papermc.io/downloads


**Versions 1.8.8 - 1.15.2 have been patched in the download API. All legacy builds are unsupported. Download at your own risk.**

API: https://papermc.io/api

We recommend using the official fix for versions older than 1.16.5 that cannot update:

https://www.minecraft.net/en-us/article/important-message--security-vulnerability-java-edition

An example test if it's working, running `say ${date:YYYY}` in console should output exactly that and not 2021. If it outputs 2021 you have not fixed the issue properly.

Plugins bundling their own versions of libraries can likely be impacted by this\**

\*(Current knowledge indicates that in ***all versions of Java, this can allow remote code execution***, so please make sure that you patch your servers __ASAP__)

Since updating Paper 1.17.1 and Waterfall to the latest log4j patches, Waterfall no longer relays the Paper `server closed` disconnect message when Paper shuts down, instead disconnecting players with `[Proxy] Lost connection to the server.`

I also observe that Paper kicks players right at the end of the shutdown. I can't remember if this was the behaviour before. Perhaps it is too late for Waterfall to receive the kick message?

```yaml
[08:32:40 INFO]: [CoreProtect] Success! Disabled CoreProtect v20.1
[08:32:40 INFO]: Saving players
[08:32:40 INFO]: Player lost connection: [kick message] # <-----------------------------
[08:32:40 INFO]: Saving worlds
[08:32:40 INFO]: Saving chunks for level 'ServerLevel[world]'/minecraft:overworld
[08:32:41 INFO]: Saving chunks for level 'ServerLevel[world_nether]'/minecraft:the_nether
[08:32:41 INFO]: Saving chunks for level 'ServerLevel[world_the_end]'/minecraft:the_end
[08:32:41 INFO]: ThreadedAnvilChunkStorage (world): All chunks are saved
[08:32:41 INFO]: ThreadedAnvilChunkStorage (DIM-1): All chunks are saved
[08:32:41 INFO]: ThreadedAnvilChunkStorage (DIM1): All chunks are saved
[08:32:41 INFO]: ThreadedAnvilChunkStorage: All dimensions are saved
[08:32:42 INFO]: Flushing Chunk IO
[08:32:42 INFO]: Closing Thread Pool
[08:32:42 INFO]: Closing Server
```

The side effect of this problem is that other plugins aren't able to act on players disconnecting during a shutdown like they used to prior to updating to the log4j patch.
An example of this is DiscordSRV not showing player disconnects

message.content:
Higher power draw is because Nvidia wanted to not have *just* a 14% perf increase from Turing (that's the perf/watt increase from Turing to Ampere). Tho, I'd say its a nice step in the right direction. Having GPUs power capped to all hell isnt fun. For example, 550w - 600w 2080Ti (XOC vBIOS and on a custom loop/AIO is good enough for cooling) can match a stock 3080 in benchmarks (which translates to game perf), 450w - 600w 3080 (modded vBIOS or shunt mod with custom loop) can match a stock 3080Ti and sometimes stock 3090 in benchmarks (also translates to game perf). 

However, the perf/watt increase from Turing to Ampere for rasterization was pretty terrible, worst we've had in a while. Rest of the GPU generations had good perf increase. Pascal to Turing was actually still good, but felt bad due to price/perf increase.

There was a zero-day attack that affected every minecraft server and minecraft client in the entire world. Every compromised piece of software that uses log4j (Minecraft being one of them) can be injected with any type of code.

Servers tend to be notified much faster as all the owners scrambled to fix it the moment someone started malware injecting the first few. Minecraft clients on the other hand, take longer to be alerted. That means any player that joins a server while compromised can still be exposed to malicious code by untrustworthy servers.

message.content: The G1 Collector: The Garbage first collector (G1) introduced in JDK 7 update 4 was designed to better support heaps larger than 4GB. The G1 collector utilises multiple background threads to scan through the heap that it divides into regions, spanning from 1MB to 32MB (depending on the size of your heap). This collector is turned on using the ‚ÄìXX:+UseG1GC flag. This strategy the chance of the heap being depleted before background threads have finished scanning for unused objects, in which case the collector will have to stop the application which will result in an STW collection. The G1 also has another advantage that is that it compacts the heap on-the-go, something the CMS collector only does during full STW collections. Another beautiful optimisation which was just out with Java 8 update 20 for is the G1 Collector String deduplication. Since strings (and their internal char[] arrays) takes much of our heap, a new optimization has been made that enables the G1 collector to identify strings which are duplicated more than once across your heap and correct them to point into the same internal char[] array, to avoid multiple copies of the same string from residing inefficiently within the heap. You can use the -XX:+UseStringDeduplicationJVM argument to try this out.

This is a very complicated process, so I suggest using the Java Argument Generator to start out, but for how each argument works, I too am not very clear, so I'm going to only cover the two garbage collectors, which I looked up in here, feel free to suggest down below!
The CMS Collector: This algorithm uses multiple threads (‚Äúconcurrent‚Äù) to scan through the heap (‚Äúmark‚Äù) for unused objects that can be recycled (‚Äúsweep‚Äù). The biggest concern when using this collector is encountering promotion failures which are instances where a race condition occurs between collecting the young and old generations. If the collector needs to promote young objects to the old generation but hasn‚Äôt had enough time to make space clear it,  it will have to do so first which will result in a full STW collection ‚Äì the very thing this CMS collector was meant to prevent. To make sure this doesn‚Äôt happen you would either increase the size of the old generation (or the entire heap for that matter) or allocate more background threads to the collector for him to compete with the rate of object allocation. Another downside to this algorithm in comparison to the parallel collector is that it uses more CPU in order to provide the application with higher levels of continuous throughput, by using multiple threads to perform scanning and collection. For most long-running server applications which are adverse to application freezes, that‚Äôs usually a good trade off to make. Even so, this algorithm is not on by default. You have to specify XX:+USeParNewGC to actually enable it. If you‚Äôre willing to allocate more CPU resources to avoid application pauses this is the collector you‚Äôll probably want to use, assuming that your heap is less than 4Gb in size.  However, if it‚Äôs greater than 4GB, you‚Äôll probably want to use the last algorithm ‚Äì the G1 Collector
